#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:11
msgid "Package Settings (packages.yaml)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:13
msgid ""
"Spack allows you to customize how your software is built through the "
"``packages.yaml`` file.  Using it, you can make Spack prefer particular "
"implementations of virtual dependencies (e.g., MPI or BLAS/LAPACK), or you "
"can make it prefer to build with particular compilers.  You can also tell "
"Spack to use *external* software installations already present on your "
"system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:20
msgid "At a high level, the ``packages.yaml`` file is structured like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:22
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  package1:\n"
"    # settings for package1\n"
"  package2:\n"
"    # settings for package2\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  all:\n"
"    # settings that apply to all packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:33
msgid ""
"So you can either set build preferences specifically for *one* package, or "
"you can specify that certain settings should apply to *all* packages. The "
"types of settings you can customize are described in detail below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:37
msgid ""
"Spack's build defaults are in the default ``etc/spack/defaults/packages."
"yaml`` file.  You can override them in ``~/.spack/packages.yaml`` or ``etc/"
"spack/packages.yaml``. For more details on how this works, see :ref:"
"`configuration-scopes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:46
msgid "External Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:48
msgid ""
"Spack can be configured to use externally-installed packages rather than "
"building its own packages. This may be desirable if machines ship with "
"system packages, such as a customized MPI that should be used instead of "
"Spack building its own MPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:53
msgid ""
"External packages are configured through the ``packages.yaml`` file. Here's "
"an example of an external configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:56
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  openmpi:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64+debug\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3-debug\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.6.5%intel@10.1 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.6.5-intel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:68
msgid ""
"This example lists three installations of OpenMPI, one built with GCC, one "
"built with GCC and debug information, and another built with Intel. If Spack "
"is asked to build a package that uses one of these MPIs as a dependency, it "
"will use the pre-installed OpenMPI in the given directory. Note that the "
"specified path is the top-level install prefix, not the ``bin`` subdirectory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:75
msgid ""
"``packages.yaml`` can also be used to specify modules to load instead of the "
"installation prefixes.  The following example says that module "
"``CMake/3.7.2`` provides cmake version 3.7.2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:79
msgid ""
"cmake:\n"
"  externals:\n"
"  - spec: cmake@3.7.2\n"
"    modules:\n"
"    - CMake/3.7.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:87
msgid ""
"Each ``packages.yaml`` begins with a ``packages:`` attribute, followed by a "
"list of package names.  To specify externals, add an ``externals:`` "
"attribute under the package name, which lists externals. Each external "
"should specify a ``spec:`` string that should be as well-defined as "
"reasonably possible.  If a package lacks a spec component, such as missing a "
"compiler or package version, then Spack will guess the missing component "
"based on its most-favored packages, and it may guess incorrectly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:96
msgid ""
"Each package version and compiler listed in an external should have entries "
"in Spack's packages and compiler configuration, even though the package and "
"compiler may not ever be built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:102
msgid "Extra attributes for external packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:104
msgid ""
"Sometimes external packages require additional attributes to be used "
"effectively. This information can be defined on a per-package basis and "
"stored in the ``extra_attributes`` section of the external package "
"configuration. In addition to per-package information, this section can be "
"used to define environment modifications to be performed whenever the "
"package is used. For example, if an external package is built without "
"``rpath`` support, it may require ``LD_LIBRARY_PATH`` settings to find its "
"dependencies. This could be configured as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:114
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mpich:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: mpich@3.3 %clang@12.0.0 +hwloc\n"
"      prefix: /path/to/mpich\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        environment:\n"
"          prepend_path:\n"
"            LD_LIBRARY_PATH: /path/to/hwloc/lib64"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:126
msgid ""
"See :ref:`configuration_environment_variables` for more information on how "
"to configure environment modifications in Spack config files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:131
msgid "Prevent packages from being built from sources"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:133
msgid ""
"Adding an external spec in ``packages.yaml`` allows Spack to use an external "
"location, but it does not prevent Spack from building packages from sources. "
"In the above example, Spack might choose for many valid reasons to start "
"building and linking with the latest version of OpenMPI rather than continue "
"using the pre-installed OpenMPI versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:138
msgid ""
"To prevent this, the ``packages.yaml`` configuration also allows packages to "
"be flagged as non-buildable.  The previous example could be modified to be:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:142
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  openmpi:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64+debug\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3-debug\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.6.5%intel@10.1 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.6.5-intel\n"
"    buildable: False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:155
msgid ""
"The addition of the ``buildable`` flag tells Spack that it should never "
"build its own version of OpenMPI from sources, and it will instead always "
"rely on a pre-built OpenMPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:161
msgid ""
"If ``concretizer:reuse`` is on (see :ref:`concretizer-options` for more "
"information on that flag) pre-built specs include specs already available "
"from a local store, an upstream store, a registered buildcache or specs "
"marked as externals in ``packages.yaml``. If ``concretizer:reuse`` is off, "
"only external specs in ``packages.yaml`` are included in the list of pre-"
"built specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:166
msgid ""
"If an external module is specified as not buildable, then Spack will load "
"the external module into the build environment which can be used for linking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:169
msgid ""
"The ``buildable`` does not need to be paired with external packages. It "
"could also be used alone to forbid packages that may be buggy or otherwise "
"undesirable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:175
msgid "Non-buildable virtual packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:177
msgid ""
"Virtual packages in Spack can also be specified as not buildable, and "
"external implementations can be provided. In the example above, OpenMPI is "
"configured as not buildable, but Spack will often prefer other MPI "
"implementations over the externally available OpenMPI. Spack can be "
"configured with every MPI provider not buildable individually, but more "
"conveniently:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:184
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mpi:\n"
"    buildable: False\n"
"  openmpi:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64+debug\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3-debug\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.6.5%intel@10.1 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.6.5-intel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:198
msgid ""
"Spack can then use any of the listed external implementations of MPI to "
"satisfy a dependency, and will choose depending on the compiler and "
"architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:202
msgid ""
"In cases where the concretizer is configured to reuse specs, and other "
"``mpi`` providers (available via stores or buildcaches) are not wanted, "
"Spack can be configured to require specs matching only the available "
"externals:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:206
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mpi:\n"
"    buildable: False\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - one_of: [\n"
"        \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\",\n"
"        \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64+debug\",\n"
"        \"openmpi@1.6.5%intel@10.1 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      ]\n"
"  openmpi:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.4.3%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64+debug\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.4.3-debug\n"
"    - spec: \"openmpi@1.6.5%intel@10.1 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\"\n"
"      prefix: /opt/openmpi-1.6.5-intel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:226
msgid ""
"This configuration prevents any spec using MPI and originating from stores "
"or buildcaches to be reused, unless it matches the requirements under "
"``packages:mpi:require``. For more information on requirements see :ref:"
"`package-requirements`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:234
msgid "Automatically Find External Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:236
msgid ""
"You can run the :ref:`spack external find <spack-external-find>` command to "
"search for system-provided packages and add them to ``packages.yaml``. After "
"running this command your ``packages.yaml`` may include new entries:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:240
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  cmake:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: cmake@3.17.2\n"
"      prefix: /usr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:248
msgid ""
"Generally this is useful for detecting a small set of commonly-used "
"packages; for now this is generally limited to finding build-only "
"dependencies. Specific limitations include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:252
msgid ""
"Packages are not discoverable by default: For a package to be discoverable "
"with ``spack external find``, it needs to add special logic. See :ref:`here "
"<make-package-findable>` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:255
msgid ""
"The logic does not search through module files, it can only detect packages "
"with executables defined in ``PATH``; you can help Spack locate externals "
"which use module files by loading any associated modules for packages that "
"you want Spack to know about before running ``spack external find``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:260
msgid ""
"Spack does not overwrite existing entries in the package configuration: If "
"there is an external defined for a spec at any configuration scope, then "
"Spack will not add a new external entry (``spack config blame packages`` can "
"help locate all external entries)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:269
msgid "Package Requirements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:271
msgid ""
"Spack can be configured to always use certain compilers, package versions, "
"and variants during concretization through package requirements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:275
msgid ""
"Package requirements are useful when you find yourself repeatedly specifying "
"the same constraints on the command line, and wish that Spack respects these "
"constraints whether you mention them explicitly or not. Another use case is "
"specifying constraints that should apply to all root specs in an "
"environment, without having to repeat the constraint everywhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:282
msgid ""
"Apart from that, requirements config is more flexible than constraints on "
"the command line, because it can specify constraints on packages *when they "
"occur* as a dependency. In contrast, on the command line it is not possible "
"to specify constraints on dependencies while also keeping those dependencies "
"optional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:290 ../../../packages_yaml.rst:556
msgid ""
"FAQ: :ref:`Why does Spack pick particular versions and variants? <faq-"
"concretizer-precedence>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:295
msgid "Requirements syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:297
msgid ""
"The package requirements configuration is specified in ``packages.yaml``, "
"keyed by package name and expressed using the Spec syntax. In the simplest "
"case you can specify attributes that you always want the package to have by "
"providing a single spec string to ``require``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:302
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  libfabric:\n"
"    require: \"@1.13.2\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:308
msgid ""
"In the above example, ``libfabric`` will always build with version 1.13.2. "
"If you need to compose multiple configuration scopes ``require`` accepts a "
"list of strings:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:312
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  libfabric:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - \"@1.13.2\"\n"
"    - \"%gcc\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:320
msgid ""
"In this case ``libfabric`` will always build with version 1.13.2 **and** "
"using GCC as a compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:323
msgid ""
"For more complex use cases, require accepts also a list of objects. These "
"objects must have either a ``any_of`` or a ``one_of`` field, containing a "
"list of spec strings, and they can optionally have a ``when`` and a "
"``message`` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:327
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  openmpi:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - any_of: [\"@4.1.5\", \"%gcc\"]\n"
"      message: \"in this example only 4.1.5 can build with other compilers\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:335
msgid ""
"``any_of`` is a list of specs. One of those specs must be satisfied and it "
"is also allowed for the concretized spec to match more than one. In the "
"above example, that means you could build ``openmpi@4.1.5%gcc``, "
"``openmpi@4.1.5%clang`` or ``openmpi@3.9%gcc``, but not "
"``openmpi@3.9%clang``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:341
msgid ""
"If a custom message is provided, and the requirement is not satisfiable, "
"Spack will print the custom error message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:344
msgid ""
"$ spack spec openmpi@3.9%clang\n"
"==> Error: in this example only 4.1.5 can build with other compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:349
msgid "We could express a similar requirement using the ``when`` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:351
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  openmpi:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - any_of: [\"%gcc\"]\n"
"      when: \"@:4.1.4\"\n"
"      message: \"in this example only 4.1.5 can build with other compilers\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:360
msgid ""
"In the example above, if the version turns out to be 4.1.4 or less, we "
"require the compiler to be GCC. For readability, Spack also allows a "
"``spec`` key accepting a string when there is only a single constraint:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:364
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  openmpi:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - spec: \"%gcc\"\n"
"      when: \"@:4.1.4\"\n"
"      message: \"in this example only 4.1.5 can build with other compilers\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:373
msgid "This code snippet and the one before it are semantically equivalent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:375
msgid ""
"Finally, instead of ``any_of`` you can use ``one_of`` which also takes a "
"list of specs. The final concretized spec must match one and only one of "
"them:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:378
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mpich:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - one_of: [\"+cuda\", \"+rocm\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:385
msgid ""
"In the example above, that means you could build ``mpich+cuda`` or "
"``mpich+rocm`` but not ``mpich+cuda+rocm``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:389
msgid ""
"For ``any_of`` and ``one_of``, the order of specs indicates a preference: "
"items that appear earlier in the list are preferred (note that these "
"preferences can be ignored in favor of others)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:395
msgid ""
"When using a conditional requirement, Spack is allowed to actively avoid the "
"triggering condition (the ``when=...`` spec) if that leads to a concrete "
"spec with better scores in the optimization criteria. To check the current "
"optimization criteria and their priorities you can run ``spack solve zlib``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:402
msgid "Setting default requirements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:404
msgid ""
"You can also set default requirements for all packages under ``all`` like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:407
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    require: '%clang'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:413
msgid "which means every spec will be required to use ``clang`` as a compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:415
msgid ""
"Requirements on variants for all packages are possible too, but note that "
"they are only enforced for those packages that define these variants, "
"otherwise they are disregarded. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:419
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - \"+shared\"\n"
"    - \"+cuda\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:427
msgid ""
"will just enforce ``+shared`` on ``zlib``, which has a boolean ``shared`` "
"variant but no ``cuda`` variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:430
msgid ""
"Constraints in a single spec literal are always considered as a whole, so in "
"a case like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:432
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    require: \"+shared +cuda\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:438
msgid ""
"the default requirement will be enforced only if a package has both a "
"``cuda`` and a ``shared`` variant, and will never be partially enforced."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:441
msgid ""
"Finally, ``all`` represents a *default set of requirements* - if there are "
"specific package requirements, then the default requirements under ``all`` "
"are disregarded. For example, with a configuration like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:445
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - 'build_type=Debug'\n"
"    - '%clang'\n"
"  cmake:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - 'build_type=Debug'\n"
"    - '%gcc'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:457
msgid ""
"Spack requires ``cmake`` to use ``gcc`` and all other nodes (including "
"``cmake`` dependencies) to use ``clang``. If enforcing ``build_type=Debug`` "
"is needed also on ``cmake``, it must be repeated in the specific ``cmake`` "
"requirements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:464
msgid "Setting requirements on virtual specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:466
msgid ""
"A requirement on a virtual spec applies whenever that virtual is present in "
"the DAG. This can be useful for fixing which virtual provider you want to "
"use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:469
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mpi:\n"
"    require: 'mvapich2 %gcc'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:475
msgid ""
"With the configuration above the only allowed ``mpi`` provider is ``mvapich2 "
"%gcc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:477
msgid ""
"Requirements on the virtual spec and on the specific provider are both "
"applied, if present. For instance with a configuration like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:480
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mpi:\n"
"    require: 'mvapich2 %gcc'\n"
"  mvapich2:\n"
"    require: '~cuda'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:488
msgid "you will use ``mvapich2~cuda %gcc`` as an ``mpi`` provider."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:492
msgid "Conflicts and strong preferences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:494
msgid ""
"If the semantic of requirements is too strong, you can also express \"strong "
"preferences\" and \"conflicts\" from configuration files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:497
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    prefer:\n"
"    - '%clang'\n"
"    conflict:\n"
"    - '+shared'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:506
msgid ""
"The ``prefer`` and ``conflict`` sections can be used whenever a ``require`` "
"section is allowed. The argument is always a list of constraints, and each "
"constraint can be either a simple string, or a more complex object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:510
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    conflict:\n"
"    - spec: '%clang'\n"
"      when: 'target=x86_64_v3'\n"
"      message: 'reason why clang cannot be used'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:519
msgid ""
"The ``spec`` attribute is mandatory, while both ``when`` and ``message`` are "
"optional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:523
msgid ""
"Requirements allow for expressing both \"strong preferences\" and "
"\"conflicts\". The syntax for doing so, though, may not be immediately "
"clear. For instance, if we want to prevent any package from using "
"``%clang``, we can set:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:527
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    require:\n"
"    - one_of: ['%clang', '@:']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:534
msgid ""
"Since only one of the requirements must hold, and ``@:`` is always true, the "
"rule above is equivalent to a conflict. For \"strong preferences\" we need "
"to substitute the ``one_of`` policy with ``any_of``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:544
msgid "Package Preferences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:546
msgid ""
"In some cases package requirements can be too strong, and package "
"preferences are the better option. Package preferences do not impose "
"constraints on packages for particular versions or variants values, they "
"rather only set defaults. The concretizer is free to change them if it must, "
"due to other constraints, and also prefers reusing installed packages over "
"building new ones that are a better match for preferences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:559
msgid ""
"Most package preferences (``compilers``, ``target`` and ``providers``) can "
"only be set globally under the ``all`` section of ``packages.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:562
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    compiler: [gcc@12.2.0, clang@12:, oneapi@2023:]\n"
"    target: [x86_64_v3]\n"
"    providers:\n"
"      mpi: [mvapich2, mpich, openmpi]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:571
msgid ""
"These preferences override Spack's default and effectively reorder "
"priorities when looking for the best compiler, target or virtual package "
"provider. Each preference takes an ordered list of spec constraints, with "
"earlier entries in the list being preferred over later entries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:576
msgid ""
"In the example above all packages prefer to be compiled with ``gcc@12.2.0``, "
"to target the ``x86_64_v3`` microarchitecture and to use ``mvapich2`` if "
"they depend on ``mpi``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:580
msgid ""
"The ``variants`` and ``version`` preferences can be set under package "
"specific sections of the ``packages.yaml`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:583
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  opencv:\n"
"    variants: +debug\n"
"  gperftools:\n"
"    version: [2.2, 2.4, 2.3]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:591
msgid ""
"In this case, the preference for ``opencv`` is to build with debug options, "
"while ``gperftools`` prefers version 2.2 over 2.4."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:594
msgid ""
"Any preference can be overwritten on the command line if explicitly "
"requested."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:596
msgid ""
"Preferences cannot overcome explicit constraints, as they only set a "
"preferred ordering among homogeneous attribute values. Going back to the "
"example, if ``gperftools@2.3:`` was requested, then Spack will install "
"version 2.4 since the most preferred version 2.2 is prohibited by the "
"version constraint."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:605
msgid "Package Permissions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:607
msgid ""
"Spack can be configured to assign permissions to the files installed by a "
"package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:610
msgid ""
"In the ``packages.yaml`` file under ``permissions``, the attributes "
"``read``, ``write``, and ``group`` control the package permissions. These "
"attributes can be set per-package, or for all packages under ``all``. If "
"permissions are set under ``all`` and for a specific package, the package-"
"specific settings take precedence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:616
msgid ""
"The ``read`` and ``write`` attributes take one of ``user``, ``group``, and "
"``world``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:619
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  all:\n"
"    permissions:\n"
"      write: group\n"
"      group: spack\n"
"  my_app:\n"
"    permissions:\n"
"      read: group\n"
"      group: my_team"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:631
msgid ""
"The permissions settings describe the broadest level of access to "
"installations of the specified packages. The execute permissions of the file "
"are set to the same level as read permissions for those files that are "
"executable. The default setting for ``read`` is ``world``, and for ``write`` "
"is ``user``. In the example above, installations of ``my_app`` will be "
"installed with user and group permissions but no world permissions, and "
"owned by the group ``my_team``. All other packages will be installed with "
"user and group write privileges, and world read privileges. Those packages "
"will be owned by the group ``spack``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:642
msgid ""
"The ``group`` attribute assigns a Unix-style group to a package. All files "
"installed by the package will be owned by the assigned group, and the sticky "
"group bit will be set on the install prefix and all directories inside the "
"install prefix. This will ensure that even manually placed files within the "
"install prefix are owned by the assigned group. If no group is assigned, "
"Spack will allow the OS default behavior to go as expected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:654
msgid "Assigning Package Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:656
msgid "You can assign class-level attributes in the configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:658
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mpileaks:\n"
"    package_attributes:\n"
"      # Override existing attributes\n"
"      url: http://www.somewhereelse.com/mpileaks-1.0.tar.gz\n"
"      # ... or add new ones\n"
"      x: 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:668
msgid ""
"Attributes set this way will be accessible to any method executed in the "
"package.py file (e.g. the ``install()`` method). Values for these attributes "
"may be any value parseable by yaml."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packages_yaml.rst:672
msgid ""
"These can only be applied to specific packages, not \"all\" or virtual "
"packages."
msgstr ""
